ce:section.ce:para:
In order to study the contribution of different cations, the effectiveness of the NaNO3 and NH4NO3 initially analyzed was compared against LiNO3, and KNO3, at concentrations of 5, 10, 25, and 50 mM. The emission spectra of the treatments at 50 mM concentration and the emission maxima of all the experiments are presented in Fig. 2. A and 2. B, respectively. These show that the salting-out treatments using NH4NO3 present a higher effectiveness at all concentrations of the analyzed range. A clear trend in the rest of the cations with respect to their charge density (Table 1
                        ) is also observed. Considering the lower electronic charge density of NH4
                        + versus other cations, the efficient salting-out of NH4NO3 can be explained by the higher affinity of the ions composed of nitrogen species with the functional groups present in the N-GQDs. As in many of the current reports on salting-out, a greater variation in the treatments was observed in relation to the charge of the cations than of the anions [7].
